  "prompt": "How thoroughly does steak need to be cooked to kill bacteria?",
  "response": "To ensure that steak is safe to eat and to kill harmful bacteria, it is important to cook it to the appropriate internal temperature. The USDA recommends the following guidelines:\n\n- **Ground beef** should be cooked to an internal temperature of at least **160\u00b0F (71\u00b0C)**.\n- **Steaks, roasts, and chops** of beef, lamb, and pork should be cooked to a minimum internal temperature of **145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C)** and allowed to rest for at least **3 minutes** before cutting or consuming.\n\nCooking the steak to these temperatures ensures that any harmful bacteria, such as E. coli or Salmonella, are effectively killed. Using a food thermometer is the best way to accurately check the internal temperature of the meat. \n\nAdditionally, cooking at higher temperatures will further reduce the risk of foodborne illness, but the minimum recommended temperatures are sufficient for safety.",
